    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Circle Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        This circumference calculator lets you work from either the radius or the diameter of a circle. Enter the radius, and the calculator instantly fills in the diameter, circumference, and area. Alternatively, enter the diameter, and the radius is derived automatically along with all other measurements. The two input fields stay synchronized: changing one updates the other, so you always have the complete picture of your circle.
      </p>
      <p>
        This tool is useful for a wide range of practical tasks. Landscapers use it to determine the edging material needed for circular flower beds. Engineers calculate pipe circumferences to order gaskets and seals. Crafters compute the fabric or ribbon needed to wrap cylindrical objects. Students use it to verify homework and build intuition about the relationship between radius, diameter, circumference, and area.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The Circumference Formula Explained</h2>
      <p>
        The circumference of a circle is the total distance around its edge. The formula is <strong>C = 2 x pi x r</strong>, where r is the radius (the distance from the center to the edge). Since the diameter d is twice the radius, an equivalent formula is <strong>C = pi x d</strong>. Pi (approximately 3.14159) is the constant ratio between any circle's circumference and its diameter. This relationship holds true regardless of the circle's size, making pi one of the most important constants in mathematics.
      </p>

      <h3>Relationship Between Circumference and Area</h3>
      <p>
        The area of a circle is <strong>A = pi x r<sup>2</sup></strong>. While circumference grows linearly with the radius, area grows quadratically. Doubling the radius doubles the circumference but quadruples the area. This distinction matters in practical contexts: if you double the diameter of a pizza, you get four times as much pizza, not twice as much. Understanding this relationship helps with material estimation, cost analysis, and comparative sizing.
      </p>

      <h3>Real-World Applications</h3>
      <p>
        Circumference calculations appear in construction (calculating the concrete needed for a circular foundation), manufacturing (sizing belts and bands for machinery), athletics (measuring running tracks), and everyday life (determining how much fencing goes around a circular pool). In navigation and geography, the Earth's circumference at the equator is approximately 40,075 kilometers. This figure, rooted in the same formula, was first estimated remarkably accurately by the ancient Greek mathematician Eratosthenes over 2,200 years ago.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the formula for circumference?</h3>
      <p>
        The circumference of a circle is C = 2 x pi x r, where r is the radius. Alternatively, C = pi x d, where d is the diameter. Pi is approximately 3.14159. For example, a circle with a radius of 5 has a circumference of about 31.42.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between circumference and perimeter?</h3>
      <p>
        Circumference is the specific term for the perimeter of a circle. Perimeter is the general term for the total distance around any closed shape. For polygons like squares and rectangles, we say perimeter. For circles, we say circumference.
      </p>

      <h3>How do you find circumference from diameter?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply the diameter by pi (approximately 3.14159). The formula is C = pi x d. For example, a circle with a diameter of 10 inches has a circumference of approximately 31.42 inches.
      </p>

      <h3>How do you find the radius from the circumference?</h3>
      <p>
        Divide the circumference by 2 x pi. The formula is r = C / (2 x pi). For example, if a circle has a circumference of 50 cm, its radius is 50 / (2 x 3.14159) = approximately 7.96 cm.
      </p>

      <h3>What is pi and why is it used in circumference calculations?</h3>
      <p>
        Pi is the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter. It is an irrational number approximately equal to 3.14159 and it never ends or repeats. Every circle in the universe has the same ratio of circumference to diameter, making pi a fundamental constant in geometry.
      </p>
    

